Consider the problem. We are given a sequence of integers $a_j$ such that $1 \le a_j \le 2015$ and $k+a_k \neq \ell+a_\ell$ for $k \ne \ell$. We need to find $b, N$ such that for $n > m \ge N$, $|\sum_{j=m+1}^n (a_j - b)| \le 1007^2$.

Let $C = 2015$. Define $f(k) = k + a_k$. The conditions imply $f$ is injective and $k+1 \le f(k) \le k+C$.
Let $U_n = \{1, \dots, n+C\} \setminus \{f(1), \dots, f(n)\}$.
Since $f$ maps $\{1, \dots, n\}$ injectively into $\{1, \dots, n+C\}$, and $|U_n| = (n+C) - n = C$.
The elements of $U_n$ are the "missing values" or "holes" up to $n+C$.
Since $f(k) \ge k+1$, if $x \in U_n$ and $x \le n+1$, then $x$ will never be in the image of $f$ for any $k > n$ (as $f(k) \ge n+2$). Thus, the "small" holes stabilize.
Let $H$ be the set of integers that are not in the image of $f$. $H$ is finite with $|H| \le C$.
Let $b = |H|$. Then $1 \le b \le C$.
For large $n$, $U_n$ consists of $H$ (all $\le n$) and a set $I_n$ of values $> n$.
$|I_n| = C - b$.
Also $I_n \subset \{n+2, \dots, n+C\}$ because $f(k) \le n+C$ for $k \le n$, but elements of $I_n$ are not images of $k \le n$. They are not images of $k > n$ either (by definition of being in $U_n$, they are missing from $\{f(1)\dots f(n)\}$? No, $U_n$ are values in range not hit by $1..n$. If they are hit by $k>n$, they are removed later. But $I_n$ are the ones in $U_n$).
Actually, $U_n$ are the values $\le n+C$ not in $\{f(1), \dots, f(n)\}$.
These are exactly $H \cap [1, n+C]$ and $\{f(k) \mid k > n, f(k) \le n+C\}$.
For large $n$, $H \subset [1, n]$, so $U_n = H \cup I_n$ where $I_n = \{f(k) \mid k > n, f(k) \le n+C\}$.
$I_n \subset [n+2, n+C]$.
We derived $\sum_{j=1}^n (a_j - b) = \text{const} - \sum_{y \in I_n} (y-n)$.
Let $W_n = \{y-n \mid y \in I_n\} \subset \{2, \dots, C\}$. $|W_n| = C-b$.
The sum is bounded by the span of sums of subsets of size $C-b$ from $\{2, \dots, C\}$.
The span is $(C-b)(b-1)$. Max value is $1007^2$.

