Let $p = |U|$. Since $S_k \ge 2$, $1 \in U$, so $p \ge 1$.
For large $n$, let $Z_n$ be the set of holes in $(n, n+C]$. The size of $Z_n$ is constant $q = C - p$.
We define $b = p$. (Actually $b = C-q = p$).
We can show that $\sum_{j=1}^n (a_j - b) = \text{const} - \sum_{z \in Z_n} (z-n)$.
Let $Q_n = \sum_{z \in Z_n} (z-n)$. Since $Z_n \subset (n, n+C]$, the values $z-n$ are distinct integers in $\{1, \dots, C\}$.
The range of sums of $q$ distinct integers from $\{1, \dots, C\}$ is an interval of length $q(C-q)$.
However, since $1 \in U$, the value 1 is never a "transient" hole, so $z-n \neq 1$ is not quite right because $U$ is stationary while the window moves.
Correct logic: The sum oscillates. The magnitude is bounded by the max variation of $Q_n$.
The maximum variation is $q(C-q)$.
We choose $q = C - p$.
Since $1 \in U$, $p \ge 1$, so $q \le C-1$.
Also if $p$ is small, $q$ is large.
The problem statement bounds by $1007^2 = ((C-1)/2)^2$.
The max variation $q(C-q)$ for $q \in \{1, \dots, C-1\}$ is indeed bounded by roughly $C^2/4$.
